<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     11-05 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0306</SECOND>
<UNK>Reports Flight 103 Bomb Originated in Cyprus</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British newspaper claimed Sunday the bomb that
destroyed Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland began its deadly journey
in Cyprus in a suitcase loaded onto a Cyprus Air jet.
   The Sunday Correspondent, citing unidentified police sources,
reported investigators have largely discounted theories published
last week that the bomb was put on board an Air Malta flight on
Malta before being transferred to the Pan Am flight.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, taking on
passengers and luggage flown in from other areas on international
``feeder flights.''
   The passengers and bags were transferred at London's Heathrow
Airport to the New York-bound Boeing 747 that was ripped apart over
Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people on board
and 11 on the ground.
   The weekly said the bomb apparently was placed in one of several
suitcases that went aboard one of two feeder flights from Cyprus to
Frankfurt.
   It said at least four U.S. intelligence agents died on Flight
103 and they had boarded the feeder flights in Larnaca. Three of
the agents were reported to have been returning from an undercover
mission believed to be connected with the U.S. hostages in Lebanon,
it said.
   The Sunday Correspondent said investigators suspect that a
suitcase belonging to one of the agents was substituted at Larnaca
airport for the suitcase containing the bomb.
   Another British weekly, The Sunday Times, reported last week
that there was a Maltese connection in the bombing. It said the
baggage list showed one suitcase was transferred to Flight 103 by
an Air Malta plane that originated in Malta.
   The Sunday Times, quoting unidentified British sources, said the
bomb was placed in a suitcase that contained clothing made and
purchased in Malta.
</TEXT>
