<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-RollerCoaster     11-05 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Roller Coaster,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrill Seekers Line Up to Ride Giant Dipper First Time After Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-Rebuilding, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrill seekers lined up Saturday to
ride the Giant Dipper roller coaster for the first time since last
month's earthquake and declared it tame compared to what they
survived.
   ``At least you always know what's going to happen with the Giant
Dipper. You come back to where you started and you can get back on
if you want,'' said Diane Rossi. ``With an earthquake, you just
don't know.''
   Mrs. Rossi and her 8-year-old daughter, Teresa, were among about
1,000 people who visited the city's boardwalk amusement park for a
benefit for victims of the earthquake that struck the San Francisco
Bay area Oct. 17.
   The quake, centered north of this seaside community, measured
7.1 on the Richter scale, killed at least 66 people and did at
least $7 billion in property damage.
   The 1924-vintage roller coaster on white wooden trestles, which
is listed on the National Register of Historic Places, was
untouched by the quake, as were most of the other rides along the
boardwalk, including a carousel built in 1911 that also is on the
register.
   Visitors paid $5 for unlimited rides on the amusement park's
first open day since the quake, and proceeds will go to earthquake
relief, said Ann Parker, spokeswoman for the Santa Cruz Seaside
Co., the owner of the park.
   ``A lot of people in this community are still putting their
lives together,'' Ms. Parker said. ``We're hoping that some of
those people come out here, even for a half hour, and have a little
fun.''
   Bob Hinde of neighboring Scotts Valley and his sons, Josh, 10,
and Jason, 15, ran from the exit to the entrance of the Giant
Dipper, riding it again and again. They said they wouldn't be
surprised if they managed at least 20 rides before the afternoon
was over.
   ``This was the first ride we went on when we got here,'' Hinde
said. ``I came up here after the quake and checked it to see if it
was all right. It looked like it was. Now I know it is.''
</TEXT>
