<FIRST>r i AM-China-Students     11-05 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Students,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Adds Restriction On Students Seeking To Go Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students wanting to study abroad who must first
take an English-language proficiency test will have to provide a
letter of permission from their department, Chinese sources said
Sunday.
   It is an additional government measure to tighten controls over
overseas study programs. Limitations were adopted after the army
crushed student-led pro-democracy demostrations last June.
   An official of the State Education Commission confirmed that a
rule demanding such a letter of authorization recently went into
effect. He did not elaborate.
   The sources said non-students must have a letter from their work
unit or, if unemployed, from their neighborhood committee if they
want to take the Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL).
   The sources said at least one Beijing student had his request
for a letter rejected by his department because he was on a
``problem list'' of students involved in some way in the spring
demonstrations.
   So many students want to take the TOEFL that some must hold
places in line for up to a week just to register.
   The test, required by most universities in the United States and
other English-speaking countries that accept foreign students, is
usually given three times a year in Beijing. Students are now
registering for a January examination.
   The government also requires a registration fee of $29, the
equivalent of a month's salary for most workers.
   Government officials have claimed there is no change in the
policy of sending students and academics abroad, but some spoke of
``necessary adjustments'' after the June crackdown.
   Most government scholarships now are going to older research
students and scholars applying for short-term programs. It is
virtually impossible for undergraduates to gain permission for
overseas studies.
   Premier Li Peng said in September that those being sent abroad
should be mainly visiting scholars and researchers because they are
older and more mature politically.
   The government is also said to be shifting foreign study
destinations away from the West and toward socialist countries.
   About half the 80,000 Chinese studying abroad now are in the
United States. Many in the West have been outspoken in criticizing
the government for the crackdown on dissent.
   The number of students refusing to return to China is expected
to increase.
   Last week the government moved to extend its monitoring of
self-supporting students abroad _ the least likely to return to
China _ by announcing that such students must register at the
Chinese Embassy or consulate within the next six months.
</TEXT>
