<FIRST>r a AM-ExamThreats     11-05 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exam Threats,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Threats Force Postponement of Doctors' Certification Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Certifying exams for at least 2,000 emergency room doctors
across the country have been postponed because of threats to the
physicians and to those who were to give the test, authorities said.
   Doctors who were to travel to eight cities for the tests Sunday
and Monday were notified there would be no exam, the American Board
of Medical Specialties announced from its headquarters in East
Lansing, Mich. A date for a re-test hasn't been set.
   The organization, as well as participants and the FBI, said
threatening letters were mailed to participants.
   ``This decision was based on the possibility of harm to
individuals related to the examinations and concerns for security
at all examination sites,'' the board said in a news release Friday.
   The exams _ for doctors who have finished specialty training in
emergency medicine _ were scheduled in Arlington, Va.; Atlanta;
Chicago; Dallas; Dearborn, Mich.; Los Angeles; Philadelphia; and
San Francisco.
   The FBI has begun an investigation, said Joseph Valiquette, a
spokesman for the bureau's New York office.
   ``It's just weird that a threat would be made at this kind of
thing,'' said John Bogdan, of the FBI's New York office. ``It would
be synonymous with threatening to do something at an SAT exam.''
   One of those threatened, Rebecca Martin, a Waterloo, Iowa,
physician who had planned to take the test in Chicago, said she was
shocked by the letter and disappointed because she'd spent months
preparing for the exam.
   ``When I opened the letter I thought it was a hoax,'' Ms. Martin
said. ``Have I been studying for the test? That's probably the
understatement of the year.''
   This is the first time a medical specialty examination has had
to be canceled, said Dr. Don Langsley, director of the American
Board of Medical Specialties, which oversees the 23 specialty
boards in the United States.
</TEXT>
