<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     11-05 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Supporters Vow More Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto MLA2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of supporters of Ferdinand
Marcos gathered in a Manila park on Sunday to denounce a police
crackdown on an earlier rally and to protest the ``hatred, greed
and terror'' of the government.
   About 1,500 followers of the late president held an
``indignation rally'' at Bonifacio park after troops used water
cannons and tear gas to break up a march by hundreds of Marcos
loyalists the day before.
   The protesters had gathered at national police headquarters late
Friday for an all-night rally, and police moved in after they
refused to disperse early Saturday.
   The rallies came as President Corazon Aquino left on an official
visit Saturday to the United States and Canada to drum up foreign
investment and convince leaders her country is stable.
   The Marcos loyalists are urging that Mrs. Aquino allow the
former president's body to be buried in the Philippines.
   Marcos, who ruled the country for 20 years, died in exile in
Hawaii on Sept. 28 at age 72. Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow his
body to be brought to the Philippines for burial.
   Ilocos Norte Vice Governor Rolando Abadilla, leader of the
march, said in a statement Sunday ``there is a growing number of
concerned citizens who are angered by the reign of hatred, greed
and terror.''
   He said his group is seeking ``radical, sweeping reforms'' to
eliminate what he said was corruption in the government of Mrs.
Aquino, who was swept to power in a military-civilian revolt that
toppled Marcos in 1986.
   ``The objective of the next People's March for Justice, which is
ending a reign of hatred, greed and terror, is now in order and
shall be launched in due time on a national level,'' Abadilla said.
   ``The fight for true justice, peace, freedom and democracy shall
definitely continue,'' said Abadilla, former Philippine
Constabulary colonel who headed the Metropolitan Command
Intelligence and Security Group.
   In a related development, Marcos' son, Ferdinand Marcos Jr.,
issued a statement published in a local newspaper condemning the
dispersal of Saturday's protest.
   ``By choosing to violently disperse the peaceful march and vigil
of tens of thousands of justice-seeking Filipinos, she (Mrs.
Aquino) has chosen force as a way to arbitrate the divisions in our
country,'' Marcos said.
   Mrs. Aquino said the show of force by Marcos' followers did not
diminish her confidence in her government's stability.
   More than 25,000 people attended the rally. It was the largest
demonstration by Marcos supporters in the capital since shortly
after his ouster.
</TEXT>
