<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Defense     11-05 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Defense,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Japan Needs to Strengthen Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu told thousands of
sailors Sunday that Japan needs to solidify its defenses as the
Soviets improve their forces and regional conflicts persist.
   Kaifu, who is also commander of the 270,000-member Japanese
Self-Defense Force, was among 6,600 people, including officials
from 46 countries, at a navy review on the force's 35th anniversary.
   In his speech, Kaifu acknowledged progress in disarmament talks
between the United States and the Soviet Union.
   However, he added, ``The international situation still remains
complicated and fluid as the Soviet Union continues to hold
enormous military power and is modernizing its war potential. Also,
regional conflicts in the world are far from fundamental
settlements.''
   In this situation, Kaifu said, Japan, as an important member of
the West, must contribute to safeguarding peace and security in the
world.
   However, he made no specific proposals.
   The United States, which has a defense treaty with Japan, has
urged the Japanese to do more for their own defense. However,
military spending is a controversial issue in Japan.
   The Japanese constitution, adopted in 1946 during the U.S.
occupation, renounces war and the use of force in settling
international disputes.
