<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     11-05 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Seven in Armenian Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police broke up a protest by several dozen
Armenian nationalists Sunday who demonstrated near the Kremlin in
support of their exiled leader. Seven people were arrested.
   About 50 Armenian protesters, members of the Organization of
National Self-Determination, waved Armenian flags and held banners
supporting nationalist leader Paryur Ayrikyan.
   The group demonstrated without interference for about 30 minutes
on the steps of Lenin Library. But riot police stopped them from
marching to nearby Red Square and twice pushed them through the
doors and down the stairs of a subway station.
   Police ripped banners away and dragged away two protesters who
resisted. They detained five more who subsequently refused to
disperse.
   The nationalists said they had not requested permission from
authorities to hold the demonstration. ``We didn't ask anybody's
permission. We don't ask, we demand,'' said demonstrator Igor
Grigoryan of Moscow.
   Police were negotiating with a handful of demonstrators to
disperse them more than an hour after the protest began. They told
demonstrators they were willing to release those who had been
arrested if the group dispersed.
   One demonstrator, Lev Gambaryan, entered a bus where the
arrested protesters were being held and he said they did not want
to come out.
   Ayrikyan, a former political prisoner, was arrested in Moscow
earlier this spring and exiled to Ethiopia. He now lives in the
United States.
   Grigoryan said Ayrikyan founded the Organization of National
Self-Determination.
   Armenia is one of 15 Soviet republics, many of which are seeking
greater autonomy from Moscow.
