<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     11-05 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Paralyzes Capital, Police Club Street Actors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used steel-tipped batons to
break up a satirical street play held as part of an anti-government
strike Sunday, and at least 15 people were hurt, witnesses said.
   About 300 people were on a Dhaka street watching the play, a
satire about President Hussain Muhammad Ershad, when police moved
in and dispersed the crowd, witnesses said.
   The actors and audience fled in panic as police charged, and at
least 15 people suffered injuries, witnesses said.
   The dawn-to-dusk strike, the 61st this year, was called by the
Bangladesh Nationalist Party and its allies to demand an end to
Ershad's 7-year-old government and to press for free elections.
   No private vehicles were on the roads, but a small number of
rickshaws, the traditional form of transportation for most
commuters, and some state-owned buses plied the streets under
police escort.
   The strike affected major cities across Bangladesh, including
the southern port city of Chittagong and the country's
third-largest city, Khulna, said opposition sources.
   There were no reports of major violence, but police said
students at Dhaka University, a hotbed of political unrest, set
fire to about a dozen rickshaws and cars that defied the strike.
   In Dhaka, a city of 6 million people, the strike began
peacefully. But paramilitary units and thousands of armed police
patrolled the city's major streets in one of the biggest shows of
strength seen recently.
   The strike was backed by several opposition groups including the
seven-party alliance in which the Nationalist Party is a major
component. The party was toppled by Ershad in a bloodless military
coup in 1982.
   Ershad has dismised opposition demands for his resignation but
indicated he would be willing to hold elections if all major
political parties agreed to participate. Opposition parties,
however, have refused to take part in polling under the current
government.
   In 1986, four years after seizing power, Ershad was elected to a
five-year term as president in an election opposition parties
charge was fraudulent.
   As in the past, the government ured citizens to ignore Sunday's
strike, and several pro-government organizations distributed
leaflets and posters showing how strikes hurt the country's fragile
economy.
   The government has said each strike costs this impoverished
nation about $78 million.
   Bangladesh is one of the world's poorest countries, with its 110
million people earning an average annual income equivalent to about
$150.
   Another anti-government strike is planned by opposition parties
Friday.
</TEXT>
