<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     11-05 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thirty-Six Killed in Tamil Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Tamil guerrilla groups battled
with guns in eastern Sri Lanka on Sunday, and at least 36 were
killed and 15 seriously injured, officials said.
   The fighting in the villages of Tampiluvil and Tamputte, both
about 20 miles southeast of Ampara, was the first clash between
rival Tamil groups since Indian peacekeeping soldiers left the area
two weeks ago.
   Military officials said about 50 members of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest rebel group, raided two camps
run by rivals and killed 30 men. The two camps are about a
half-mile apart, they said.
   Six Tamil Tigers also were killed in the fighting, said the
officials who cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   The camps aparently are run by a group known as the Tamil
National Army, a militia organized by former rebels to try to
maintain order in the violence-wracked area.
   The officials said the attackers abducted about 30 men of the
Tamil National Army.
   Residents in Ampara, 125 miles east of Colombo, said an
unofficial curfew was being enforced in the town and that all shops
were closed.
   A Tamil Tiger leader in Colombo confirmed the attack. ``Action
has been taken to dismantle the illegal Tamil National Army,'' he
said.
   The Sri Lankan Army commander, Lt. Gen. Hamilton Wanasinghe,
said troops were sent to the two villages. The soldiers will ``take
necessary action and see that there is no repetition'' of such
incidents, Wanasinghe said.
   India withdrew about 4,000 soldiers from the Ampara district
last month, heightening fears of renewed bloodshed between Tamil
groups.
   The latest fighting marked a new phase in the 6-year-old
struggle by the Tamil Tigers and other guerrilla groups for a
separate Tamil homeland in the north and east.
   Most groups gave up the armed struggle under an India-mediated
accord in July 1987. The Tamil Tigers briefly accepted the
agreement but then turned their guns on Indian soldiers, who had
been sent to Sri Lanka to supervise the accord.
   The Indians' numbers swelled from 2,000 to about 100,000 as the
Tamil Tigers began attacking them. The Indian force has been
periodically withdrawn in batches and the remaining 36,000 soldiers
are scheduled to leave by Dec. 31.
   As the deadline advances, concern has been mounting over who
will keep peace in the area. Sri Lanka's small army is tied down in
its own battle against Sinhalese radicals in the south.
   Tamil Tigers are currently engaged in peace talks with the
Sinhalese-dominated government in Colombo.
   Their demand for a separate nation grew out of complaints of
discrimination by the majority Sinhalese in jobs and education.
Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
