<DOCNO> AP891105-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-IthacaMayor     11-05 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ithaca Mayor,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Candidate Likely Next Mayor of Ithaca, N.Y.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben Nichols doesn't mind being labeled a
socialist.
   But the man who is likely to be Ithaca's next mayor is quick to
emphasize that he's a democratic socialist _ a member and former
chairman of the Democratic Socialists of America.
   ``The key word is democratic,'' Nichols said in a recent
interview.
   The retired engineering professor defeated three-term incumbent
John C. Gutenberger by a convincing 56-to-44 percent margin in the
Democratic primary in September. He will face Jean Cookingham, a
former attorney for the Federal Housing Administration, in
Tuesday's general election in this college town of 30,000.
   The man who was known as the only socialist mayor in the nation,
Bernard Sanders of Burlington, Vt., stepped down in March after
serving four terms. Sanders, however, ran on a third-party ticket
dubbed the Progressive Coalition while Nichols is running as a
Democrat.
   In Ithaca, where registered Democrats outnumber Republicans by
more than a 2-to-1 margin, Nichols appears to have the election
sewn up.
   Nichols says being a socialist won't directly affect his actions
as mayor. But the socialist label, he said, ``does indicate what my
priorities are.''
   Those priorities include strong support for labor, the homeless
and minorities. Nichols also thinks real estate developers should
help pay for low-cost housing, and wants new laws to protect
tenants.
   ``My interests are much more those of the working people than
the prerogatives of business,'' he said. He said he is not
anti-business, but doesn't think business needs his help in getting
its voice heard.
   Nichols, who is midway through his first term on the city's
Common Council, said he also hopes to establish better relations
with Cornell University, his alma mater and former employer _ and a
major force in Ithaca.
   Cornell, he said, should pay more to the city for the services
it receives. Even if the tax-exempt university just paid for fire
services, he said, it could trim the city's property taxes.
   Not that he would reduce those taxes, Nichols added _ he'd
probably use the money for something else. More government takes
more money, although he would rather not raise property taxes,
which he considers regressive.
   ``I think we have to do a very vigorous job finding sources of
revenue other than property tax,'' he said.
   Nichols' Republican opponent criticizes his proposal to create
new government commissions, saying she believes in less government,
not more.
   ``I don't think with a tight budget that should be a high
priority,'' Cookingham said. ``I do not regard government as a
quick fix for a problem. The solutions that I have do not show a
great deal of government involvement.''
   Nichols' socialist tag hasn't been much of an issue in the
mayoral campaign, and the candidate says he doesn't expect any mass
defection of Democrats.
   ``I think it's because they know me,'' he said. ``I've been
involved in city government, I'm a known quantity. I'm not going to
do anything wild or irrational.''
</TEXT>
