<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Strikes     11-05 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ryzhkov Appeals for Reason, Minister Travels to Strike Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov on Sunday appealed to
striking coal miners in the Soviet Arctic to end a walkout that he
said endangers winter fuel supplies.
   Strikers reported that the minister of the coal industry,
Mikhail I. Shchadov, arrived in the area and that they expected a
meeting with him Monday.
   ``The situation that has arisen at present in the coal industry,
especially on the eve of winter ... creates an inadmissible
situation in ensuring vital supplies for our people,'' Ryzhkov
said. His comments were carried by the officials Tass news agency.
   Workers in the largest mine of the Pechora Basin in the Komi
region went on strike Oct. 25 to protest what they said were
government delays in fulfilling promises it made to end nationwide
mining strikes in July.
   The Pechora workers were joined last week by miners at 10 other
mines, and only two mines in the region were operating over the
weekend. Miners say more than 15,000 of them are on strike, and the
official media say the strike already has cost millions of dollars
in lost production.
   The workers also have advanced political demands, including the
removal of language in the Soviet Constitution that makes the
Communist Party the leading force of society.
   Echoing the slogans of the Bolshevik revolution, which the
country will commemorate Tuesday, they demanded that power be
turned over to local governing councils, land to farmers and
factories to workers.
   A local court declared the strike illegal but did not try to
halt it.
   Ryzhkov said the strike could lead to ``extremely grave
results.'' He did not elaborate.
   ``Appealing to your reason and workers' honor, I ask you to show
reason and a sense of civic duty for the consequences which can
arise in the country, to stop strikes, to maintain the necessary
rhythm of work, to ensure a normal life for the Soviet people,'' he
said.
   He said the Council of Ministers, or Cabinet, is keeping tabs on
fulfillment of the promises of better living and working conditions
that the government made in July.
   Government officials will meet with miners Nov. 17 to review how
well the government has kept its promises, he said.
   Vladimir Deneka, a spokesman for the strike committee in the
Komi regional capital Vorkuta, said in a telephone interview that
miners knew about Ryzhkov's appeal only from Moscow reporters who
had called to ask their reaction.
   Shchadov arrived in Vorkuta but had not yet met with miners,
Deneka added. The coal minister was studying the workers' demands
and was in contact with Moscow about them, he said.
</TEXT>
