<FIRST>r i AM-PrinceCharles     11-05 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prince Charles,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politics May Keep Charles From Speaking Out On Hong Kong Skyline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The razing of colonial buildings to make way
for a glass-and-steel skyline may irritate Prince Charles, but
politics could keep the architectural critic in him quiet during
this week's royal visit.
   The royal couple are coming to the colony despite a flare-up of
anti-British sentiment over the summer, when London made clear it
will allow only a small percentage of Hong Kong residents to settle
in Britain after China takes over the territory in 1997.
   Prince Charles and Princess Diana arrive in the British colony
Tuesday.
   They will spend much of their four-day official stay cutting
ribbons and visiting social service organizations, no doubt keenly
aware they are not to upset the colony's delicate political
situation.
   Charles has accused modern architects, planners and developers
of causing more harm to London's skyline than the German air force
did during the World War II blitz. He is to officially open a
couple of new additions to the skyline here.
   In a recently published book, Charles says many modern buildings
are devoid of character and fail to meet the needs of the people
who live and work in them.
   The prince tends to like classical-style buildings with
porticoes, columns and decorations.
   David Russell, a senior lecturer in University of Hong Kong's
architecture department, believes the prince will find much to his
dislike in the colony's architecture.
   Hong Kong's skyline is crowded with box-like office towers that
``create a completely dull and depressing environment,'' Russell
said.
   Russell views some of the newer additions, including the yawning
waterfront Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center the prince is
to officially open, and the prismatic 70-story Bank of China, as
among the ``colossal monsters of glass and steel'' going up around
Hong Kong.
   ``The human being put next to them is totally dwarfed and
rendered quite insignificant,'' he said.
   But Kellogg Wong, associate partner in the New York-based I.M.
Pei architectural firm that designed the Bank of China building,
has described it as ``a thing of beauty, a sculpture in itself.''
   Charles also will open the Hong Kong Cultural Center, a
low-slung windowless building that has been described as a ``ski
jump'' and a ``huge skateboard ramp.''
   Conservationists find this highly ironic because the center lies
on the former site of a Victorian-style railroad station they had
tried to save from destruction in the mid-1970s by appealing to the
prince's mother, Queen Elizabeth II.
   William Meacham, a former member of the official Antiquities
Advisory Board, said the station was a prominent landmark
overlooking the colony's famous harbor before it was demolished in
1978. Only the clock tower was left standing.
   Many other landmarks have been razed during Hong Kong's rapid
growth since World War II, leaving only a few of the graceful
colonial-era buildings still standing.
   But Russell and Meacham says the prince is not likely to say
anything critical.
   ``I think he was instructed to keep the visit rather low-key
because the British government certainly is not in very good odor
in Hong Kong,'' he said. ``Diplomatically, he will probably keep
his mouth shut so he won't put his foot in it.''
</TEXT>
