<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Border     11-05 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Border,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Families Pouring Over Border Into West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asssociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEB, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young East German families squeezed
into tiny sedans poured through this border town toward West
Germany early Sunday, abandoning a homeland in which they had lost
trust.
   East German Trabant cars arrived at the rate of 30 to 40 an hour
at the border crossing to northern Bavaria, almost all of them
packed with people in their 20s or early 30s, many with young
children.
   ``We heard the news at nine last night, and by 11 we were
gone,'' said a 26-year-old woman from Schwerin, in the north of
East Germany.
   She, her husband, their two sons and a friend drove all night to
Cheb. Here, they met several other families and young people, who
like them, had leapt into their cars once they heard they could
travel freely to West Germany for the first time in their lives.
   ``My friend woke me up at two in the morning,'' said a
21-year-old from Annaberg, close to the Czechosolovak border. ``He
were are,'' he said with a grin.
   All the people interviewed expressed no confidence in their
Communist leadership at home, even if it does introduce reforms.
   ``My wife and I are leaving because we lost any hope that the
GDR (East Germany) will meet our expectations in life,'' said an
earnest 32-year-old worker from Leipzig.
   He recounted how his last hopes vanished the night of Oct. 3-4,
when he saw police beat children as security forces battled
thousands of people trying to get into the Dresden railway station.
   They were trying to board a special train going west from Prague
through East Germany.
   ``I didn't intend to flee myself, I simply brought friends there
who wanted to leave,'' said the man, who like others interviewed
refused to give his full name. ``It was horrible.
   ``Before that, I thought there was some future in the GDR. I
earned well. But they always told us the GDR was a peaceful state,
and when you see your hopes disappointed like that, you have to
leave.''
   A few of the waiting young East Germans said they wanted to try
just to visit West Germany for a day.
   ``We decided in the bar last night,'' said one of three
well-dressed youths crammed into a stylish Soviet car fitted with
Western accouterments that spell money in the East bloc.
   ``We just want to have a cup of coffe and come back again,''
said one of his friends.
   ``We don't do badly in the GDR,'' he said, while expressing deep
skepticism about the chances of new East German leader Egon Krenz
introducing genuine change.
   ``Nobody believes him. Really, nobody,'' said the third of the
youths, who came from the town of Plauen, the site of several mass
demonstrations for democracy in recent weeks.
   But the youths were disappointed in their quest. An East German
car at the front of the 50-car line turned around at the border,
announcing that it was impossible just to visit West Germany.
   ``We lost our bet,'' one of the youths shrugged as they headed
back home.
   But most of those waiting were going to West Germany to stay.
   One 32-year-old father from Weimar took two of his children and
drove through the night, leaving his wife and two more children
behind to join the family later in West Germany.
   ``The thought (of leaving) was always there,'' he said. ``Now's
the chance. We have no trust in the whole thing (in East Germany).
As long as those people are in power, nobody has any confidence.''
</TEXT>
