<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CarrierAccident     11-05 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carrier Accident,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fear of Failure Adds to Anxiety When Pilots Make First Carrier Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulse rates quicken during any aircraft
carrier landing, but the heart-pounding is most intense during a
flight student's first time, say fellow trainees of a pilot who
crashed into the USS Lexington.
   The accident killed the student pilot, Ensign Steven E. Pontell,
23, of Columbia, Md., and four people on the flight deck.
   Pontell, stationed at Meridian, Miss., Naval Air Station, was
making his first approach to a carrier when he crashed.
   A few hours before the accident on Oct. 29, Ensign William
``Ray'' Dyer of Cookville, Tenn., was in the same position, but
landed without incident six times.
   Dyer, a student pilot at Pensacola Naval Air Station, said he
was calm and preoccupied with flying the T-2 Buckeye training jet,
the same type Pontell flew, until he turned into final approach,
called ``the groove.''
   ``I rolled into the groove and it hit me,'' Dyer said. ``I felt
my heart beat. That's the first time in a plane I've ever felt
that. I was going, `Oh my God.' It's like everything the past year
went, `whoosh,' right in front of me.''
   Studies show landing on a carrier _ in which the plane is
stopped abruptly via a hook hanging from its tail that is snared by
a cable strung across the deck _ puts greater stress on a pilot
than flying into combat, said Lt. Scott Means of Key West, an
instructor pilot at Pensacola.
   Means said a fellow pilot had the best description: ``It's a
cross between a pleasurable sex experience and a car crash.''
   Dyer said he couldn't let the crash bother him.
   ``Accidents will happen,'' Dyer said. ``It's not an
accident-free environment we live in.''
   That realization was magnified last week. The Lexington crash
was only the first of five accidents, all unrelated, involving Navy
ships and planes around the world that took seven lives in a span
of four days.
   Of all the Navy's activities, landing jets on ships may be the
most hazardous, but student pilots say crashing is not their
greatest fear.
   ``I would say the fear of failure is about 80 percent of it,''
said Ensign Bill Hiscock of Fort Lauderdale, another
Pensacola-based student pilot who made his first carrier landing
Oct. 29.
   ``If they don't do this properly there's a chance they may not
get their wings,'' Means explained. ``That's where the apprehension
comes from.''
   The consequences may be dismissal from the Navy or getting a
non-flying assignment. Historically, a jet student has rarely been
allowed to shift to helicopters or propeller-driven planes,
although the Navy may have spent up to $1 million to train him.
   ``The attitude that's taken is that the other communities ...
don't want somebody else's trash, so to speak,'' Means said. He
added however that the Navy is loosening up a bit on this tradition.
   By the time a pilot attempts a carrier landing, he has about 250
hours of flying time. All must eventually make 10 landings or
``traps'' aboard a carrier to complete their training.
   Before that, though, they make 80 touch-and-go landings on
runways painted with the outline of a flight deck. They make two
touch-and-go landings on the carrier before their first trap, all
without instructors because flying solo builds confidence, Means
said.
   Seeing the carrier for the first time can be intimidating, as it
looks so tiny from the air.
   ``I wanted so much to look down at the ship to see what it
looked like, and I just said, `I can't do it''' Dyer recalled.
   The hook hanging from the plane's tail is supposed to catch one
of four cables strung across the deck, bringing the jet to a dead
stop from about 120 mph in two seconds.
   Even though their ultimate aim is to stop, pilots push their
throttles to full power as soon as the wheels touch _ so they can
fly off the other end of the angled deck if they miss the cables.
   ``The first trap was a surprise. I didn't think I'd stop,'' Dyer
said. ``I ... hit the deck and the next thing you know I'm stopping
and a guy's running out to me, (shouting) `Power back! Power back!'
I had froze on the controls. And then finally, I said, `OK, I'm
safe. I'm down. I'm stopped.' ''
</TEXT>
