<DOCNO> AP891105-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Defense-Glance     11-05 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense-Glance,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Congress Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at-a-glance, is a comparison of the $305
billion defense bill approved by House and Senate negotiators and
the military blueprint sought by President Bush for fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>STRATEGIC DEFENSE INITIATIVE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The conference report, which still must be approved by the full
House and Senate, slashes $1.1 billion from Bush's request of $4.9
billion for the antimissile shield in the fiscal year that began
Oct. 1. The cut of 7 percent from the fiscal 1989 total marks the
first year that the program has suffered a decrease since former
President Reagan introduced Star Wars six years ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>B-2 STEALTH BOMBER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate conferees agreed to two B-2 bombers in fiscal
1990 _ one less than the Bush administration sought _ and money for
parts for five bat-winged aircraft in fiscal 1991. The defense bill
also cuts about $400 million from the program and imposes test
standards that must be met before the production line moves into
high gear.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MX RAIL-GARRISON SYSTEM AND MIDGETMAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush sought about $1.1 billion for the multiple-warhead,
rail-garrison MX and some $100 million for the single-warhead,
truck-based Midgetman. The defense bill sets up a $1.1 billion
strategic pot for the two land-based, nuclear missiles, about $150
billion less than the administration's request, and gives Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney discretion on how to allocate the money. The
bill also adopts House language imposing a limit of 50 on the
number of deployed MX missiles.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>F-14D JET FIGHTER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bush had sought to cancel the Navy's carrier fighter, and
congressional negotiators concurred _ starting in fiscal 1991. The
defense bill calls for 18 F-14Ds in fiscal 1990, which began Oct.
1, but none in fiscal 1991. The legislation also requires the
manufacturer, Grumman Corp., of New York, to sign a clause
terminating the program after the 18 fighters.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>V-22 OSPREY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The defense bill provides $255 million in research and
development money for this other conventional program that Bush
tried to kill, but no new procurement money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
