<FIRST>r a AM-ElRukns     11-05 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-El Rukns,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Round of Federal Indictments Latest Blow to Powerful Chicago Gang</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The El Rukns dominated the streets like no other
gang in city history, controlling a thriving drug trade with
ruthless efficiency for nearly 25 years. But officials are hoping
their reign is finally ending.
   Law-enforcement authorities say their latest offensive _ two
sweeping federal indictments _ affected most of the gang's top
ranks. Scores of arrests followed the Oct. 27 indictments charging
65 gang members and associates with counts that include
racketeering, conspiracy and murder.
   The indictments charge that gang members committed 20 murders,
attempted others and intimidated witnesses to control drug
trafficking on the city's South and West sides with links to five
states _ traffic worth hundreds of thousands of dollars a week in
street sales.
   Gang members who killed on their leaders' orders will testify
for the prosecution when the case goes to trial, probably next
summer, authorities say.
   ``We have definitely put a nail in the coffin,'' said Chicago
Police Capt. Ron Jablon, who led the raid on the Fort, the El
Rukns' fortified headquarters.
   Several defendants have already pleaded guilty. And the gang's
roster of 250-300 hard-core members already was depleted by
convictions and criminal charges.
   But the death knell has sounded before and the El Rukn gang has
been able to endure for more than two decades, creating a street
legend of violence, drug traffic worth millions each year, and even
international intrigue including an attempt to help out Libya.
   ``These guys are unique,'' said a federal official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``They grew up from little gang-bangers to
a major organized criminal enterprise that lived by shootings and
murders.''
   Also, if the indictments cut into the upper echelons, others
could step in.
   ``You're never going to eliminate street gangs completely, and
the sort of mystique of the El Rukn organization is going to be
hard to kick in a community where it's flourished for 25 years,''
said the official.
   Attorney James Graham, representing defendant Michael Sardin,
complained that the government is picking on a bunch of middle-aged
men who might once have been involved in the gang, but are now
associates at most.
   ``They're trying to clean the streets up of anybody that could
go back and revitalize the El Rukns,'' Graham said.
   One of the gang associates indicted is Noah Robinson, half
brother of two-time Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson.
Robinson was charged with offering the El Rukns money to kill two
men _ one of whom was slain _ and with supplying narcotics to the
gang's drug operation.
   The gang began in the mid-1960s on the mostly black South Side.
First called the Blackstone Rangers, it evolved into the P Stone
Nation, an amalgamation of several gangs whose leaders ruled
together.
   During that period of black pride, activism and power, two
members attended then-President Nixon's 1969 inaugural, and the
gang received federal funds for job-training programs.
   But the use of those funds was called into question, and leader
Jeff Fort received a five-year sentence for fraud.
   Fort became a Moslem in prison, and formed the El Rukn gang upon
his release in 1976, naming it for the cornerstone of a shrine at
Mecca.
   Authorities say Islam did not slow gang activity, though El Rukn
inmates once filed a federal lawsuit seeking permission to hold
religious services in prison. A federal judge ruled in 1986 that it
would be too dangerous to allow them to assemble.
   In 1987, Fort and four other El Rukns were convicted of
conspiracy and weapons charges, accused of offering to commit
terrorist acts for Libya against the United States.
   Fort _ who oversaw the effort from a Texas prison in coded
telephone conversations _ was sentenced to 80 years in prison.
   At the time, a Cook County prosecutor declared the gang was
``crumbling'' and that all their leaders were in jail.
   In November 1988, Fort was sentenced to 75 years for involvement
in the 1981 slaying of a rival drug dealer.
   And still the El Rukn gang rumbled on.
   Authorities say the gang uses hit squads to systematically
eliminate drug-trade competitors, and that the latest spate of
arrests may help resolve as many as 50 murder cases dating to the
late 1960s.
   Some officials put the toll at more than 100.
   The El Rukn headquarters is sealed and targeted for razing. The
site may become a playground.
</TEXT>
