<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     11-05 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Traffickers Reportedly Planned to Kidnap President's Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said drug traffickers planned to
kidnap one of President Virgilio Barco's daughters and a leading
presidential candidate as part of a major offensive, Colombia's
biggest newspaper reported Sunday.
   The newspaper, El Tiempo, cited police and senior government
officials as the sources for the story. A national police
spokeswoman told the Associated Press by telephone that she could
not confirm the report.
   The plots by the Medellin cartel were intended to prevent the
government from launching extraditions of drug suspects to the
United States, El Tiempo said. The traffickers' assassination Aug.
18 of another leading presidential hopeful sparked a crackdown that
foiled the cartel's plans, El Tiempo reported. That crackdown also
began a series of extraditions to the United States.
   The paper, which has a reputation of gaining access to
high-level officials, said police learned of the plot from suspects
trying to gain immunity from prosecution in the Aug. 18
assassination of presidential candidate Sen. Luis Carlos Galan.
   The paper said the offensive planned by the Medellin drug cartel
began with the slaying of Galan, along with the killings of a
federal judge and a state police commander the week before.
   Traffickers initiated the plan after determining that the
government planned to begin extraditions, the paper said.
   ``The chiefs of the Medellin cartel planned the kidnapping of
President Barco's daughter and the presidential candidate Hernando
Duran Dussan,'' the newspaper said.
   Barco's three daughters, Carolina, Diana and Julia, have all
reportedly left Colombia. Carolina owns a house in Bogota's
colonial section. Despite reports of her absence, at least six
soldiers with automatic rifles guard the house constantly.
   Hernando Duran Dussan, a 70-year-old presidential candidate from
Barco's Liberal Party, leads the polls in the presidential race to
be decided in May of next year.
   A strong opponent of negotiations with drug traffickers, Duran
Dussan said recently that he has received several death threats. He
did not identify any specific group as being behind the threats.
   The paper said Duran Dussan was to be kidnapped during a
political rally.
   In addition to the kidnappings, the Medellin cartel planned to
have assassins kill the head of the country's investigative police,
Col. Oscar Pelaez Carmona; the chief of its secret police, Gen.
Miguel Maza Marquez; and the head of the Communist Party, Gilberto
Vieira, El Tiempo said.
   The cartel targeted Maza Marquez in a car bombing May 30 that
killed seven people on a main avenue in Bogota. The police chief,
uninjured in the attack, has since led Barco's law enforcement
assault on traffickers.
   President Barco has issued decrees allowing the extradition of
traffickers to the United States and the confiscation of their
property in Colombia.
   Police and army troops have raided hundreds of farms, houses and
apartments in the weeks after the government crackdown began,
driving traffickers underground and disrupting their operations.
</TEXT>
