<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Executions     11-05 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Executions,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Alleged CIA Spies Executed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran executed four alleged U.S. spies
during celebrations marking the 10-year anniversary of the seizure
of the U.S. Embassy in Tehran, Iranian news media reported Sunday.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency said the alleged CIA agents
were hanged Saturday in Tehran.
   The news agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the four men were
tried, convicted and sentenced to death by a ``special military
court.'' It did not elaborate.
   It identified them as Touraj Riyahi, Kyanoush Hakimi Bushehri,
Ardeshir Ashraf and Ibrahim Moshtaqi.
   It quoted an unnamed Information Ministry source as saying all
four had aided the United States during Iran's war with Iraq, which
ended with a tentative cease-fire last year.
   The source said the purported spies ``put valuable intelligence
information at the disposal of the Central Intelligence Agency
during the war to help Iraq and facilitate terrorist activities in
Iran.''
   He added that the defendants' testimony ``showed that the U.S.
is continuing its hostile activities and interventions against the
Islamic Republic of Iran.''
   The agency did not say when or where the four were arrested. It
also did not provide further details of their activities.
   In April, President Hashemi Rafsanjani, then Parliament speaker,
announced that a spy ring had been broken and its members arrested.
   He and other Iranian officials have refused to give the number
of those detained, saying such information may prove useful to the
CIA.
   More than 20 alleged spies have claimed they worked for the CIA
in televised confessions screened in Iran in the past few months.
They all said they were recruited by U.S. Embassy personnel while
working abroad or while seeking visas for the United States at
embassies in Europe and Asia.
   Some of the alleged defendants were identified as army and air
force officers. Others were civilians.
   On Saturday, authorities displayed seven reputed spies at the
former U.S. Embassy compound in downtown Tehran in an attempt to
whip up anti-American passion on the anniversary of the takeover of
the mission by radicals on Nov. 4, 1979.
   The militants held 52 American diplomats and embassy personnel
hostage inside the compound 444 days.
</TEXT>
