<FIRST>r a AM-SFQuake-Japanese     11-05 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Japanese,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese University Students Travel From Tokyo to Help Earthquake
Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SF Quake-Legislature, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Masafumi Higashi saw the images
of toppled buildings and collapsed freeways on Japanese television
last month, he was compelled to help the victims of the Bay area
earthquake.
   ``My first reaction was to come here,'' said the 25-year-old
English major from Chuo University in Tokyo. ``I felt it was my
duty.''
   Higashi came, along with 32 other fellow students, each paying
about $750 of their own money for air fare.
   Japan Airlines offered the students that low-price round-trip
fare when it learned of their mission to help victims of the Oct.
17 earthquake, Higashi said. Toshiba donated two computers to the
cause.
   Also in the student group was Isao Suzuki, 64, who built fighter
airplanes for the Japanese air force during World War II. He said
he wanted to repay a debt to the American people.
   ``The younger generation today in Japan has forgotten the debt
that we owe to America,'' Suzuki said Friday through an
interpreter. ``A big part of the reason we've been able to develop
into the country we are today is that America helped us.''
   Seven students arrived in California on Oct. 26 and the rest
arrived Wednesday after obtaining necessary passports and funds.
   After talking to disaster officials in San Francisco, the first
wave of students learned the big city was saturated with
volunteers. Their help was most needed in hard-hit Santa Cruz
County to the south, particularly in the small farming town of
Watsonville.
   They eventually wound up at Watsonville's Salvation Army
headquarters, where workers last week were still distributing food
and other essentials daily to about 300 earthquake-devastated
families.
   ``As soon as they arrived here from the airport, they wanted to
start work right away,'' Salvation Army Capt. Kirk Suarez said of
the students, who at times have accounted for as much as half the
volunteer staff laboring at agency headquarters near downtown.
   ``I'm really fortunate to have them here,'' Suarez said.
``They've done a lot of work. I'm amazed at their energy.''
   Aid from Japan is coming in the form of money as well as people
Japanese companies so far have pledged nearly $9.3 million in
donations to the earthquake relief effort, according to officials
of the Consulate General of Japan.
   Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. and Sony Corp. each has
pledged $1 million, with other companies offering equipment or
relief donations from $75,000 to $500,000, said officials at the
Japan Information Center in San Francisco.
   The students said they have worked about eight hours a day,
seven days a week since their arrival.
   They have spent their nights at a Salvation Army shelter in
nearby Scotts Valley.
   Every morning, Suzuki wakes them up and leads them in an old
Japanese army cheer, which translates as ``let's do our best.''
   Their work of sorting donated clothing and packing boxes of food
has not left the students time to see California, but they said
they have observed and learned during their short time in
Watsonville.
   ``We came here to work, not for sightseeing,'' said Nao Koike, a
20-year-old political science major. ``I will go sightseeing the
next time I come back.''
   Working in Watsonville, which has a large Hispanic population,
has shattered a lot of stereotypes for Ms. Koike.
   She said she once thought ``America was like a movie, with all
white Anglo-Saxon Protestants.''
   ``But now I know America has many kinds of people: blacks,
Asians, Hispanics,'' she said.
   For Haru Sato, a 21-year-old law student, the experience has
been ``important, valuable, interesting.''
   ``One of my biggest suprises has been to see how many people are
working here,'' Sato said. Such voluntarism is unusual in Japan,
where tight-knit families take care of their own during crises, he
said.
   Also surprising has been the optimism of the American people in
the face of disaster, said Sato.
   ``The Japanese people tend to withdraw in such circumstances;
the American people are just glad to be alive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
