<FIRST>r w AM-US-EastGermany     11-05 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-East Germany,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scowcroft Says West Germany Can Cope With Refugee Influx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House national security adviser
predicted Sunday that West Germany will be able to cope with the
thousands of East Germans refugees crossing its border, but called
the situation explosive.
   ``West Germany can handle it,'' Scowcroft said on the CBS-TV
program ``Face the Nation.'' Nevertheless, he said, ``We're making
plans for whatever might happen.
   ``It would be easy ... for something to happen, something
unexpected which could turn what is still, even despite a million
people, a relatively orderly process into chaos or an explosion,''
Scowcroft said.
   The separation of Germany into two parts since World War II has
been a recurrent source of East-West tension.
   The democratic reforms sweeping the Soviet bloc have rekindled
the ``German question'' because, said Scowcroft, ``there is no East
German nation. They distinguish themselves only by their political
and economic system so that to the extent that they reform, they
undercut their reason for existence.''
   Scowcroft predicted that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
in his planned Dec. 2-3 summit with President Bush, will not ask
the West for massive credits for Poland and Hungary as they move
out of the Soviet orbit.
   ``I don't think his intention is to throw Eastern Europe to the
West to bail out,'' said Scowcroft. ``I think he is using
developments in Poland and Hungary to bolster his own attempts at
reform.''
   Discussing administration preparations for the Gorbachev
meeting, Scowcroft said, ``We're anticipating anything he could
conceivably ask.''
   At the summit, Gorbachev would meet an angry reaction if he
informed Bush the Kremlin planned to crack down to restore
stability.
   ``What we would do is point out to him that one of the reasons
for the more favorable attitude of the administration, of the
American people, toward the Soviet Union, is the opening up ... the
tendency toward pluralism ... glasnost ... and perestroika. To the
extent that disappears, our feelings will disappear,'' said
Scowcroft.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, appearing on the NBC-TV program,
``Meet the Press,'' had the same message for Moscow.
   ``If ... the Soviet Union or any other country begins to abuse
human rights, moves in a regressive direction, they would not have
sympathy from this administration,'' said Quayle.
</TEXT>
