<DOCNO> AP891105-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1625EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Glance     11-05 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Glance,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Peace Plan At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at some of the main elements of the Lebanese
peace plan unanimously approved Sunday by Lebanon's Parliament and
brokered by the Arab League.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARLIAMENT: Increases the number of seats in the unicameral
house to 108, equally divided between Moslems and Christians. The
Parliament previously had 99 seats, with Christians holding a
slight majority.
   There are 73 surviving legislators. The majority Christians won
a 6-to-5 advantage over Moslems in all government posts when
Lebanon won independence in 1943. Moslems now make up just more
than 50 percent of the nation's population.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PRESIDENT: Strips some powers from the president, traditionally
a Christian, to give the prime minister and Parliament speaker,
both Moslems, a wider share in decision making. Strips president of
the authority to appoint and dismiss prime ministers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HOUSE SPEAKER: Increases term to four years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SYRIA: Calls for eventual, partial Syrian military withdrawal
from Moslem west Beirut and its environs. But sets no timetable for
withdrawal of Syrian troops from eastern Lebanon's Bekaa Valley _ a
persistent Christian demand.
</TEXT>
