<DOCNO> AP891105-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     11-05 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small town has gained a distinction it
would just as soon not hold: the thirstiest community in Kansas.
   Figures compiled by the state showed that in 1987 each of
Rolla's 423 residents used an average of 626 gallons of water a
day, compared with the per-person 139 gallons-a-day average
statewide.
   The 1988 estimates had Rolla residents using 599 gallons per
person, every day.
   ``There's no way we can be using that much water,'' said Rachael
Stewart, a nutritionist in the southwest Kansas city, which gets
only 16 or 17 inches of rain a year. ``When they told us that, I
didn't know whether to start rationing water, or go home and see if
I could actually use that much.''
   But since Rolla is one of about a dozen Kansas towns without
water meters, individual usage can't be measured. City Clerk
Dorothy Banker figures water bills based on lot size and number of
lines to a residence. Most folks pay $15.85 a month, regardless of
how much water they use.
   Places that don't meter water tend to use 50 percent to 70
percent more water a day than cities that charge according to use,
says the Kansas Water Office and the Division of Water Resources.
   ``This is the first year they sent my water report back, and
just flat said, `Justify this,''' said Banker.
   There is no penalty, just embarrassment, for topping the water
usage list.
   ``We do realize we have a problem, and we have taken steps to
alleviate it,'' said Kurt Waldo, Rolla's combined city manager,
chief of police and public works superintendent.
   A voluntary plan restricting lawn watering to every other day
was put in place in May and has shown some positive results, Waldo
said. ``We got people in the habit of turning the water off,
instead of just letting it run.''
   Average per capita consumption dropped from 793 gallons a day in
April to 399 gallons in June, thanks in part to some timely rains,
Waldo said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students pitched in with 114,000 old phone
books at Directory Games, a competition to reach out and bring back
the used paper for recycling.
   Two weeks remain to reach Project ReDirectory's goal of 120,000
phone books, which will be recycled into tissue and other paper
products.
   Most of the old directories were collected since Southwestern
Bell began distributing new directories Oct. 23.
   Roosevelt Elementary School won first prize of $300 at the
Directory Games on Saturday, bringing in nearly 62 tons. Jane
Longan, a teacher at Roosevelt, said students located most of the
old directories at hospitals.
   ``There were books that had never been used,'' Ms. Longan said.
   She said the effort gave students a sense of ``togetherness,''
but the victory had its less-than-glamourous moments.
   ``The worst part was loading,'' she said. Teachers, parents,
students and secretaries spent nearly all day Friday heaving the
books onto a tractor-trailer.
   Southwestern Bell spokesman Wayne Campbell said 120,000 books
would be equivalent to one-fourth of the directories distributed
last year.
   If the Tulsa project is successful, Southwestern Bell will plan
to make the same effort in Oklahoma City next year when new
directories are distributed there, Campbell said.
</TEXT>
