<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1857EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LexingtonReunion     11-05 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lexington Reunion,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crews of Today, Yesterday Remember Departed Shipmates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Carrier Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former sailors who served aboard the USS
Lexington in World War II joined with the aircraft carrier's crew
over the weekend to remember shipmates who died 45 years apart.
   The Blue Ghost Association of former crew members originally
planned its reunion to coincide with the 45th anniversary Sunday of
the day a Japanese suicide plane hit the carrier and killed 47
shipmates.
   But the heartache and horror of the wartime losses were recalled
Oct. 29 when a T-2 Buckeye training jet crashed into the Lexington.
The crash killed the Navy pilot and four people on the flight deck.
   On Sunday, a Navy chaplain offered prayers during shipboard
services to console crew members.
   The ship, now used exclusively to train naval aviators, was
given the nickname Blue Ghost during the war because Japanese
propagandist Tokyo Rose reported it sunk several times, only to
have it reappear in its unusual, uncamouflaged blue-gray paint.
   During a day cruise Saturday that was part of the reunion plans,
sailors from two eras dropped a pair of wreaths in the Gulf of
Mexico about 10 miles from where the trainer crash occurred.
   ``It's ironic,'' said Roland King of Westfield, Mass., president
of the assocation, after he and the group's vice president, Charles
Ryberg of Waltham, Mass., dropped one of the wreaths into the sea.
   About 1,500 guests, including family members of the 1,400
present and former crew members, crowded onto the ship's flight
deck to watch demonstration flights by various Navy aircraft and a
fly-over by five T-2s. One of the training jets peeled off to leave
the other four in a missing-man formation.
   The wreaths then were dropped overboard by the former crew
members and the ship's present skipper, Capt. C. Flack Logan.
   Ryberg said his thoughts during the ceremony turned to three
buddies he lost in the kamikaze attack and to the Lexington's
skipper at the time, Capt. Ernest Wheeler Litch.
   ``When we were hit that day ... I had a chance to be up near the
bridge (and) then-Captain Litch,'' Ryberg said. ``He was looking up
and there were tears coming down (from) his eyes.''
   Ryberg said he knew Logan must have felt the same way after the
crash.
   ``They are the captains and they bleed inside,'' Ryberg said.
``This captain here (Logan) bled that day for those people.''
</TEXT>
