<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Legislature Bjt   11-05 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Legislature, Bjt,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Legislature Completes Work on Quake Relief Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators wrapped up work over the
weekend on an $800 million earthquake relief package, approving a
temporary quarter-cent sales tax increase which Gov. George
Deukmejian said he would sign Monday.
   The governor, meanwhile, announced the appointment of a panel of
earthquake and engineering experts to investigate why sections of
Interstate 880 and the Bay Bridge collapsed.
   ``We also need to know whether these failures were, or could
have been predicted,'' Deukmejian said in his weekend statewide
radio address.
   The Republican governor will sign the bills Monday during a
visit to San Francisco, said spokeswoman Susie Trowbridge.
   Several Northern California legislators predicted that a
13-month, quarter-cent increase in the sales tax won' t be enough.
The tax will raise an estimated $800 million. The governor's office
also plans to tap the state reserve for $200 million.
   Those lawmakers, while lacking numbers to support their
arguments, insisted the cost of the earthquake repairs will be much
higher than the total $4.25 billion in approved federal aid and
state funds.
   ``It's going to be closer to $10 billion, believe me,'' said
Sen. Nick Petris, who urged a half-cent sales tax increase. ``This
is no time to be pandering to the pockets of the people.''
   The tax hike, opposed by most Republicans in the Assembly,
passed the lower house Saturday with only two votes to spare. It
passed the Senate on a 34-2 vote.
   ``Why would anyone want to take advantage of this disaster to
raise taxes?'' asked Assemblyman Pat Nolan, one of a group of
conservative Republicans who tried to block the tax.
   But Deukmejian, who drafted the 12-point relief package with
legislative leaders, said the funds combined with federal aid
should ``provide the necessary resources in order to restore some
semblance of normalcy in the Bay area.''
   Lawmakers recessed their special earthquake session Saturday
evening, postponing action until January on more than 90 other
earthquake-related measures introduced this week.
   California's statewide sales tax is currently 6 percent,
although the tax is as high as 7 percent in parts of the state
where local voters have approved higher levies.
   The tax will aid rebuilding from the 7.1 magnitude quake, which
struck Northern California on Oct. 17, killing 66 people and
injuring more than 3,000. State authorities have estimated the
damages at more than $7 billion, including some $1.7 billion to
state and county roads.
   One quake-related bill in the governor's package approved
Saturday would supply $19.4 million in grants to quake victims.
Other bills would earmark money to strengthen roads and bridges,
give immediate aid to people displaced by the quake and provide tax
breaks for owners of quake-damaged property.
   A mild aftershock struck the San Francisco Bay area Sunday
morning.
   Pat Jorgenson, a spokeswoman with the U.S. Geological Survey,
said the aftershock hit at 5:37 a.m. and measured 4.0 on the
Richter scale, according to a preliminary calculation. The
seismographic station at the University of California at Berkeley
estimated the strength at 4.2 on the scale.
   The quake occurred on the San Andreas fault and the epicenter
was in the area of Loma Prieta mountain, located about 8 miles
northeast of Santa Cruz, Ms. Jorgenson said.
   There were no reports of damage or injuries. A 4.0 Richter quake
is capable of moderate damage near the center.
   Meanwhile, Hispanic leaders and U.S. Rep. Leon Panetta over the
weekend blasted federal officials, saying they have ignored the
needs of the many Spanish-speaking people left homeless by the
quake.
   ``There is a Spanish population here that needs special
attention: it demands some sensitivy,'' the Democratic
representative from Monterey said during a Saturday meeting in
Santa Cruz.
   The meeting brought together federal, state and local agencies
working on earthquake relief programs.
   FEMA official Bob Stevens told the task force that the agency
ran out of Spanish-language applications while serving disaster
victims in Puerto Rico.
   Mick Jagger, lead singer of the Rolling Stones, made a surprise
stop at Watsonville's ravaged downtown and a tent-city for quake
victims before flying by helicopter back to Oakland for his Steel
Wheels concert tour Saturday.
   ``It's a bit hard to take in. It's such a small community,''
said Jagger, who flew in along with rock promoter Bill Graham two
hours before the Stones concert at the Oakland Coliseum.
   ``With 1,400 people out of work in the downtown, it affects
everyone else. People don't know quite what they'll do,'' said
Jagger, whose band has pledged $500,000 to be divided between
victims of the quake and Hurricane Hugo.
</TEXT>
