<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-05 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow and High Winds Buffet Rockies But Nice Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow and gusty winds whipped the eastern slopes of the central
Rockies on Sunday and 7 inches of snow blanketed northern
Minnesota, but most of the nation enjoyed tranquil weather.
   Snow began falling on parts of northern Minnesota Saturday
evening and early Sunday morning. It was heaviest in northeast
Minnesota, with 7 inches reported at Baudette.
   A low pressure system was producing light showers early Sunday
afternoon from eastern South Dakota and northeastern Nebraska
across southern Minnesota and northern Iowa into west-central
Wisconsin.
   Light rain fell on parts of eastern Wisconsin and upper
Michigan. Parts of North Dakota also reported light snow and snow
showers.
   Strong and gusty winds continued to whip through some of the
higher elevations of Colorado and Wyoming. Winds at the summit of
Squaw Mountain, west of Denver, hit 55 mph at sunrise.
   Temperatures were in the 70s Sunday across much of the
southeastern quarter of the nation, with readings in the 80s across
the Florida peninsula, and from south central Texas into western
Arkansas.
   Fort Worth, Texas, tied its high temperature record Sunday with
a reading of 85 degrees. San Angelo, Texas, also tied its high with
a reading of 86 degrees.
   Temperatures were in the 70s in southern Arizona and southern
California. Readings were in the 30s across much of North Dakota,
and northern and central Minnesota.
   The low for the Lower 48 states Sunday was 16 degrees at
Houlton, Maine.
</TEXT>
