<FIRST>u p AM-ElectionsRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0701 11-05 1021</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Elections Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0701,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Head to Wire in Off-Year Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 14th-15th graf pvs, bgng: ``Wilder, buoyed...'' with 4
grafs to add quotes; picks up 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``Race had...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat David Dinkins clashed in campaign debate with New York
mayoral rival Rudolph Giuliani on Sunday while gubernatorial
contenders sought support in Virginia and New Jersey in the final
days of an off-year election season focusing on race and abortion.
   Weekend polls pointed to a possible Democratic sweep on Tuesday
in the three most closely watched races _ L. Douglas Wilder of
Virginia in his bid to become the nation's first elected black
governor, Dinkins in his drive to become his city's first black
mayor and Rep. James Florio in New Jersey.
   Democratic chairman Ron Brown hailed the surveys as evidence his
party was ``moving in a new direction'' after losing last year's
presidential campaign and is able to reach voters ``in the middle
of the political spectrum.''
   GOP chairman Lee Atwater said ``I'm not going to concede
anything'' that would suggest he anticipated defeat for Giuliani,
Rep. James Courter in New Jersey or J. Marshall Coleman in
Virginia. He noted that President Bush overcame unfavorable polls
to win a pivotal Republican primary election last year on his way
to the White House.
   Atwater said no matter the outcome, this year's campaign would
portend little for 1990, when 34 Senate seats, 36 governorships and
435 House seats are on the ballot.
   On the volatile abortion issue, Atwater said, ``We're trying to
be the majority party, and we're big enough party to have differing
viewpoints on all issues, and specifically, abortion.'' He and
Brown were interviewed on ABC's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   The underdog Republicans in the big races in New York, Virginia
and New Jersey all have been thrown on the defensive by their
pro-choice opponents on the issue of abortion. The subject has
emerged as a potent issue in the wake of a Supreme Court ruling
last summer permitting tougher restrictions.
   In comments underscoring the importance of race, Brown said
Dinkins and Wilder would become leaders of ``national status'' if
they win. But he also said their fortunes would have little to do
with the future of Jesse Jackson, far and away the nation's best
known black politician.
   The off-year ballot was crowded with hundreds of city hall, city
council, and other local races as well as dozens of referendums
from Maine to California.
   Detroit's 71-year-old Mayor Coleman Young hoped to hold off an
unexpectedly strong challenge from 40-year-old rival Tom Barrow.
Cleveland City Council President George Forbes was running against
state Sen. Michael R. White in a particularly bruising fight to
pick that city's next mayor.
   In Seattle, Norm Rice is favored to become the city's first
black mayor, while state Sen. John Daniels is heavily favored to
become the first black mayor of New Haven, Conn., which is 70
percent white.
   In Texas, 11 candidates are on the ballot to fill the unexpired
term of the late Rep. Mickey Leland, killed in an airplane crash in
Ethiopia.
   But the national attention was focused on Virginia, New York and
New Jersey, where abortion, race, local issues and negative
campaign commercials proved to be a combustible mix.
   Wilder, buoyed by a Richmond Times-Dispatch poll reporting a
nine-point bulge, campaigned Sunday in the state's coal mining
region. He told voters of the region's crucial role in his upset
victory in the 1985 race for lieutenant governor.
   ``If my campaign had failed in southwest Virginia in '85, I
wouldn't be standing here as the gubernatorial nominee,'' Wilder
told a rally in Grundy. ``In '85, you gave me a start.''
   Coleman was in northwestern part of the state to conclude a
weekend in which he charged his rival with privately pledging to
coal miners he would ``sabotage'' the state's right-to-work law by
permitting unions to collect dues from nonunion workers covered by
union contracts. Wilder says he supports the right-to-work law.
   ``It's not in the bag,'' Coleman told supporters at a picnic in
Front Royal. ``We're coming around the corner. ... The undecided
are going our way overwhelmingly.''
   Race had largely been an unspoken issue in their campaign until
late week, when Coleman said Wilder was benefiting from a ``double
standard'' in press coverage.
   Wilder replied Saturday by appearing with housewife Marie Moran,
who said she had intended to vote for Coleman, but was switching
because of his comment about press coverage. ``It's time for
Virginia to have a black governor,'' she said.
   The Dinkins-Giuliani debate was their second in less than 24
hours, and came as a new public opinion poll reported a 54-38
advantage for the Democrat.
   ``I think the people of this town want a mayor who has nothing
to fear from a prosecutor,'' former U.S. attorney Giuliani said of
his rival, who concedes he failed to file income tax returns 20
years ago and has been dogged about questions of a stock transfer
to his son. Giuliani told reporters after the debate that Dinkins
``needs to be investigated.''
   But Dinkins accused his opponent of ``distortions and
complaints'' and said he had put the stock and tax questions to
rest. He noted that three of the city's four daily papers have
endorsed him and said of Giuliani, ``If he's the greatest thing
since sliced bread as he argues, why is it that they haven't turned
to him?''
   Florio, buoyed by a poll showing him with a lead of 24 points,
called for the election of Democratic candidates to the State
Assembly, where Republicans have a two-seat majority. ``Unless I
have people in the Assembly that are philosophically in line with
what I've been talking about, then I'm going to have a mission to
carry out with one hand tied behind my back,'' he said.
   Courter dismissed the Star Ledger-Eagleton poll as he made his
way around the state. In an appearance on the Brinkley program he
accused Florio of running a campaign of ``scurrilous ads'' designed
to obscure his views on possible tax increases and other issues.
</TEXT>
