<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Aquino     11-05 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aquino,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>2,000 Greet Visiting Philippine Leader in Toronto</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crowd of people chanting ``Cory! Cory!''
greeted President Corazon Aquino of the Philippines on her way to
Mass Sunday, the second day of her eight-day visit to Canada and
the United States.
   Mrs. Aquino came to Toronto from Vancouver where she arrived
Saturday to begin the trip, aimed at spurring foreign investment
and commitments to help relieve the country's $28 billion foreign
debt.
   Mrs. Aquino waved to the crowd of 2,000 outside St. Michael's
Roman Catholic Cathedral.
   On Monday she will meet Prime Minister Brian Mulroney in Ottawa.
Mrs. Aquino's press secretary, Adolfo Azcuna, said among several
agreements expected to be signed is a $56 million Canadian aid
package for social and public works projects.
   Canadian two-way trade with the Philippines reached about $189
million last year, but total Canadian investment in the country is
only $36 million, Azcuna said.
   Larry Kent, a spokesman for the Canadian government, said
security was tightened for Mrs. Aquino's arrival. He did not
elaborate.
   Mrs. Aquino, 56, was swept to power in a 1986 military-civilian
uprising that ousted President Ferdinand Marcos.
</TEXT>
