<SECOND>AM-Bush-Mother,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Summons Reporters to See Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dorothy Walker Bush, who at age 88 has
recovered this year from a minor stroke and pneumonia, was well
enough Sunday to pose for a picture with her son the president.
   ``I want you to see how well my ma looks,'' President Bush told
a pool of White House reporters he summoned to the front door of
her home here for a photo opportunity.
   Mrs. Bush, who was hospitalized for a week in September with
pneumonia, emerged in a kelly green dress and jacket, leaning on
the arms of George and his older brother, Prescott Jr.
   The president, who stopped here on his way back to the White
House after a visit to Andover, Mass., pointed to the reporters and
camera crews and said, ``These guys have to travel with us all over
the world. They seem rather good natured about it.''
   Bush, who had last seen his mother at the family's summer home
in Kennebunkport, Maine, two months ago, said, ``Well, we'd better
push on,'' kissed her on the cheek and took his leave, along with
his customary train of police, Secret Service agents and press vans.
   Bush grew up in this posh, rustic community just outside the New
York border, but not in the home where his widowed mother now lives
in.
