<FIRST>r i AM-Malta-Summit     11-05 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malta-Summit,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Advance Team for Summit Arrives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25-member White House advance team
arrived in Malta Sunday to assess the land facilities required for
the shipboard summit of President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, according to press reports.
   The summit is to be held off Malta on Dec. 2 and 3.
   Maltese newspapers said it was unlikely Bush and Gorbachev would
be on the island at the same time.
   Bush is expected to fly to Malta directly from the United States
on Dec. 1, while Gorbachev probably will arrive the next day after
a visit to Italy and the Vatican, the reports said.
   The Sunday Times said it was not known how far from land the
U.S. and Soviet warships would be but they probably would be
``within sight from shore.''
   News reports said Malta's Foreign Ministry has reserved 1,800
hotel rooms for American and Soviet staff members. Up to 2,000
journalists are expected to cover the meeting, operating from Malta.
   Officials said the White House and Kremlin both want separate
press centers for their journalists. The government is expected to
set up a press center at the Mediterranean Congress Center, which
is close to the mouth of Grand Harbour.
   Maltese newspapers are calling the Bush-Gorbachev meeting the
``post-Yalta summit.''
   U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt stopped in Malta in 1945 to
meet British Prime Minister Winston Churchill before the two
statesmen went to Yalta to map out details of the post-war
settlement with Soviet leader Josef Stalin.
   A cartoon in The Sunday Times showed Bush and Gorbachev shaking
hands with the Soviet president saying:
   ``We've come a long way George.''
   Bush replies: ``Yeah Mick ... from Yalta to Malta.''
   Malta still treasures the U.S. Army jeep thatr Roosevelt used
when he stopped in Malta before going to the Yalta conference. It
is exhibited at the island's war museum in Valletta, close to the
Mediterranean Congress Center.
</TEXT>
