<DATELINE>GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small planes collided just after taking
off from two intersecting runways at Gadsden airport Sunday,
killing all four people aboard the aircraft.
   A turboprop King Air and a Cessna collided shortly before noon
about 500 feet above the intersection of the two runways, Fire
Chief Allen Hawkins said. There is no air traffic control tower at
the airport.
   No one on the ground was injured.
   Killed aboard the Cessna were Charles William Herman, 42, of
Gadsden, and Royce L. Earwood, of Ashland, Etowah County Coroner
Bill Bragg said. Herman was taking flying lessons from Earwood, he
said.
   Robert Horton, 30, of Boaz, and Leo Dziados, 56, of Uniontown,
Ohio, were killed aboard the King Air, Bragg said. The plane was
leased by Brenlin Corp. of Akron, Ohio, parent company of the local
Gulf States Steel Corp., airport manager Fred Anderton said.
   Two officials from the National Transportation Safety Board
arrived in Gadsen to investigate the crash, said John Whiteside of
the Federal Aviation Administration's regional office in Atlanta.
