<SECOND>AM-NYC Mayoral,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayoral Candidates Clash in Second Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Elections Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican mayoral hopeful Rudolph Giuliani,
well behind in the polls with only two days to go, called Democrat
David Dinkins dishonest Sunday and promised to investigate his
financial dealings if elected.
   Dinkins bristled at what he called Giuliani's ``distortions and
complaints,'' and said he had put to rest questions about a stock
transfer to his son and his failure to file income taxes 20 years
ago.
   Dinkins, who is seeking to become the city's first black mayor,
also pointed out that three of New York's four daily newspapers
have endorsed him.
   ``Those editorial boards know me and know Mr. Giuliani and
selected Dinkins,'' he said in the opening minutes of a lively and
often contentious televised debate, the second and final one of the
campaign.
   ``If he's the greatest thing since sliced bread as he argues,
why is it that they haven't turned to him?'' Dinkins said.
   The latest poll, conducted for the Daily News and WABC-TV, shows
Dinkins leading Giuliani by 54 percent to 38 percent. The poll had
a margin of error of plus or minus 5{ percentage points.
   The winner of Tuesday's election will succeed Mayor Ed Koch, who
lost the Democratic primary to Dinkins.
   Seeking to make up ground, Giuliani opened Sunday's debate
aggressively, hitting hard at Dinkins' personal finances.
   The former U.S. attorney charged that Dinkins was involved in a
cover-up by failing to follow through on a promise to make public
more details of the stock transfer to his son. Giuliani has
questioned whether Dinkins significantly undervalued the stock in
the transfer.
   Referring to Dinkins' charge in their first debate Saturday
night that New Yorkers need ``a mayor, not a prosecutor,'' Giuliani
said, ``I think the people of this town want a mayor who has
nothing to fear from a prosecutor.''
   Talking to reporters afterward, Giuliani said he would launch a
city investigation into Dinkins' finances if elected.
   ``I think it is now quite clear that he does not have the
honesty and integrity that commends him to the voters,'' Giuliani
said.
   Told of Giuliani's pledge, Dinkins brushed it off, saying, ``I
suppose he just can't get the prosecutor out of himself. He seems
not to realize that he's running for mayor.''
   During the debate, Dinkins accused Giuliani of flip-flopping on
abortion by saying that although he personally opposed it, he would
continue city funding for abortions for poor women.
   Giuliani said his position was similar to that of other
Catholics like Gov. Mario Cuomo and Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</TEXT>
