<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TickerTalk Bjt   11-05 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ticker Talk, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market `Vigilantes' Out in Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For all the stock market's seemingly manic
behavior lately, some analysts see a message behind its madness.
   Amid the controversies over program trading and corporate
takeovers, stock traders sometimes appear to have veered off on a
through-the-looking glass digression from what is taking place
elsewhere in the economy.
   But at the same time, close followers of the financial scene
say, the market has taken on an increasingly powerful role, not
just in reacting to economic trends and government policies, but
also in helping to determine them.
   Ever since the Crash of 1987, these analysts note, the Federal
Reserve has been forced to give a lot of weight to the state of the
stock market in setting its credit policies.
   Legislators, too, have effectively been put on notice that they
can't start changing rules _ for instance, on taxes, corporate
takeovers or foreign investment in this country _ without taking
into account how stock investors might react.
   The implicit penalty for a misstep on any of these matters is a
sudden drop in stock prices that threatens far-reaching trouble for
the domestic and world economies, not to mention for any
policymakers who wind up taking the blame.
   This ``vigilante'' effect first gained wide attention in the
bond market in the early 1980s.
   In the view of many analysts, the large, amorphous group of
people who invest in bonds became increasingly fearful that the
Federal Reserve wasn't doing enough to restrain inflation.
   So they collectively refused to bid for bonds until interest
rates reached levels that restrained the growth of credit.
   ``Their market actions encouraged, or some would say compelled,
central banks to tighten to slow economic growth and prevent any
inflation resurgence,'' said Robert Barbera, economist at Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Today, we contend, it is stock market reaction to too-tight
monetary policy that at times influences monetary policy and that
reduces somewhat the risk of global recession.
   ``Thus, in the second half of the 1980s, stock market vigilantes
have replaced the bond market vigilantes of the first half.''
   Analysts say this shift was clearly demonstrated in the
aftermath of Black Monday, Oct. 19, 1987. The Fed, which had been
tightening credit before stocks crashed, abruptly began to supply
assurances of plentiful amounts of money.
   In addition, a bill that had been taking shape in Congress to
discourage some forms of takeover activity was shelved.
   Another severe selloff on Friday, Oct. 13, of this year once
again drew signals from the Fed that it would provide whatever
liquidity was necessary to stave off a market collapse.
   As time passes, ``the Fed continues to watch the stock market,''
said Darwin Beck, economist at First Boston Corp.
   All this naturally raises several issues: Who appointed bond and
stock traders to these positions of power? Can they be trusted to
use it wisely, or even responsibly? If they don't, to whom do they
have to account?
   The answer to any of those questions depends to a great extent
on the respondent's point of view.
   Defenders of the vigilantes say they are unlikely ever to engage
in any sort of conspiracy, given their sheer diversity and the fact
that they compete against each other for their livelihoods.
   Skeptics, on the other hand, can cite the history of the 1980s
as conclusive evidence of the susceptibility of unfettered markets
to abuse of many kinds.
   On one point, however, most observers agree. The modern
financial vigilante is a product of an era when many governments
around the world have promoted free markets as the best means of
making societies and economies work.
   The activities of the stock-market vigilantes now promise to be
studied in the future as a test of whether that premise is right.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891105-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-05-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CreditMarkets Bjt   11-05 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Credit Markets, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>College Savings Bond Program Provides Tax-Free Tuition Savings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starting Jan. 1, parents can take advantage of a
savings bond program that will allow them to put away money for
their children's college education tax-free.
   The program involves the U.S. Treasury's Series EE savings
bonds, which have been around for years. The difference is that
federal tax on the bonds' interest will be forgiven if the proceeds
are used for tuition. Savings bonds always are exempt from state
and local taxes.
   The program is limited to residents at least 24 years old who
meet certain income requirements: married couples with adjusted
gross incomes of $60,000 a year and under, and single people with
incomes of $40,000 and under.
   For those with higher incomes, the tax-deductibility is reduced
according to a scale. Married couples with incomes of $90,000 and
over and singles with incomes of $55,000 or more cannot participate.
   The bonds may only be bought by parents for their children;
other relatives may not participate.
   Using savings bonds to put away money for college education has
long been popular, but the 1986 federal tax code revision made it
less advantageous.
   Before the tax law changes, parents typically would buy bonds in
their child's name and declare the interest as income on tax forms
filed for their children. This way, the child usually would pay no
tax since the interest income would be lower than the child's
minimum taxable income.
   However, the revised code taxes children under age 14 at their
parents' marginal tax rate instead of at the children's rate. That
eliminated some of the tax advantage.
   The new program should restore the popularity of savings bonds
for college tuition funding, said Stephen Meyerhardt, a spokesman
for the Treasury's savings bond program.
   He said the new program is simpler than the traditional way of
putting away college funds in bonds because there is no need to
file annual tax forms for the children.
   Instead, the bonds will be bought in the parents' names and
interest will only be declared when a bond is cashed in to pay for
tuition. He said the Internal Revenue Service is still working on
rules for how this interest will be excluded from taxation.
   Series EE Treasury bonds sell for half their face value. The
face value is paid at maturity. They can be bought for as little as
$25 and are sold at most banks and savings and loans.
   Meyerhardt said the Treasury has been deluged with inquiries
about the program. ``Obviously, the potential audience is huge,''
he said last week.
   While university officials generally praise the savings plan,
they say they wish it had been extended to grandparents and
students as well.
   Richard F. Rosser, president of the National Association of
Independent Colleges and Universities, agreed there should be great
demand for the program.
   ``It's simple and it's uncomplicated,'' he said. ``This may very
well become an important savings program for just taking it out of
your monthly wages. People have bought EE bonds for years through
payroll deductions.''
   This is not the first college bond program. Several states have
marketed some of their normal state revenue bonds as tuition
savings bonds.
   These bonds, like Treasury bonds, are zero-coupon bonds, meaning
there is no annual interest payment, or ``coupon.'' That's why
they're sold at a discount, with their face amount paid at maturity.
   In Washington state, a $50 million initial offering quickly sold
out last year, said Edward Palmer, a first vice president at
Security Pacific Bank Washington, the lead manager for the bonds.
   Though a $200 million issue this year was not a sellout, Palmer
said the state and the bank consider the program ``extremely
successful.''
   ``You really feel like you're doing something for people,''
Palmer said.
   Among other states that have issued college savings bonds are
Illinois and North Carolina.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
