<HEAD>New Publisher Named at Ladies Home Journal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EST _ time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The publisher of Ladies Home Journal, Robert D.
Thomas, said Sunday he was stepping down after 12 years in the post
to ``pursue other business and publishing interests.''
   Thomas is being replaced by Donna Galotti, who had been
advertising director of the women's service magazine since joining
it in 1987.
   Thomas was said to be unavailable to discuss his plans or his
reasons for leaving the magazine, which is owned by Meredith Corp.
of Des Moines, Iowa.
   He joined the magazine's Chicago office in 1966 as an account
manager, and was western sales manager from 1971-77.
   Myrna Blyth, publishing director and editor-in-chief of the
magazine, said Galotti's selection as publisher comes after the
magazine posted a stellar advertising performance over the past 12
months.
   The November issue was the largest in the magazine's 106-year
history and brought its ad page total to 1,624 for the year, up 18
percent or 245 pages from 1988.
   ``Donna has done a tremedous job as advertising director and we
know she will be an even greater asset to the magazine as
publisher,'' Blyth said in a statement.
   Galotti said in the statement that her goal is to ``continue
breaking records in terms of ad pages and circulation.''
   She had previously been eastern manager at Woman's Day magazine.
