<FIRST>r f AM-PublicTV-TurfWars 1stLd-Writethru   11-05 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Public TV-Turf Wars, 1st Ld-Writethru,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Television Stations Fighting Over Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 15th graf, previously beginning ``For example xxx to delete
unclear reference; also moved general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public television stations, those
non-commercial bastions of civility and good taste, are taking off
the white gloves in an uncivil war over, ahem, money.
   With half the nation's viewers now able to tune in two or more
public TV channels, public TV executives increasingly are tripping
over one another as they go hat-in-hand to viewers and private
backers.
   Nearly one in five viewers can choose among four or more public
TV stations. And many of those stations are trying to raise money
by showing the same programs to the same persnickety audiences.
   ``It can strike terror in your heart when the main source of
your revenue is local fund raising (and) over-the-air pledging,''
says Peter Downey, a senior vice president at the Public
Broadcasting Service.
   The overcrowding problem has gotten bad enough that executives
from some 50 public TV stations that compete in the same cities met
in Dallas in September under the auspices of PBS to talk about
their grievances.
   Downey said the meeting, the first of its kind, was designed to
cool tensions that have been simmering over new stations in a
number of cities.
   ``The situation seems to have been getting worse in the last
four or five years,'' Downey said in a recent interview. ``The pot
just seemed to boil over a bit.''
   Downey said much of the problem stems from the Public
Telecommunications Facilities Program, which makes federal matching
funds available to help build non-profit communications projects
such as public TV stations. The fund is administered by the
National Telecommunications and Information Administration, a
Commerce Department agency.
   The fund was designed to encourage broadcasters to build public
stations in areas previously unserved. Downey said two to four
stations per year are being created, but mostly in larger
population centers.
   ``Over the years there's been a lot of talk about birth control,
to change NTIA's policies to discourage establishment of more
stations, particularly in markets already served,'' Downey said.
   There are about 40 cities in which two or more public TV
stations compete. And although there aren't any hard statistics
available on what kinds of bites these stations are taking out of
one another's audiences and donations, they all feel the pressure,
public TV executives say.
   ``We end up on the air asking the same people for donations,''
said Fred Esplin, general manager of KUED, a Salt Lake City, Utah,
public station that competes with KBYU-TV in nearby Provo. ``A few
people give to both of us, but most people give to one or the
other.''
   ``It's something that we think about all the time,'' said Joyce
Campbell, senior vice president and station manager of WETA in
Washington, where viewer donations comprise 66 percent of the
station's budget.
   At the Dallas meeting, station executives discussed pooling
facilities and staffs. PBS officials also urged them to
differentiate their programming so everyone doesn't show the same
PBS workhorses such as ``Masterpiece Theater'' and ``Nova.''
   For example, it was pointed out that WHMM in Washington, which
shares the greater Washington-Baltimore market with WETA and
Maryland Public Television, shows many programs aimed at
Washington's predominantly black audience.
   In Utah, KBYU-TV, which is owned by the Morman Church, has tried
to distance itself from the mainline PBS programming shown by KUED.
   ``We really have a children's niche and a family niche in this
market,'' station manager Mel Rogers said. ``Lassie'' and
``Flipper'' might be found on KBYU, and Rogers said the station's
Lawrence Welk show is the most popular public TV program in Utah.
``KUED aims more for the yuppie market.''
   KYBU and KUED have agreed to hold regular ``summit meetings'' to
discuss differences and, sometimes, divvy up programs.
   One sore point that competing public stations haven't resolved
is program costs. Stations buy programs from PBS based upon their
ability to pay, which means newer stations usually pay less for the
same programs than their more entrenched competitors.
   Don Johnson, president of KRMA-TV in Denver, estimated that his
station pays ``three to four times as much per program'' for the
same programs as Denver's smaller public station, KBDI-TV. There is
nearly 50 percent duplication of programming between the two
stations, Johnson said.
   He said PBS was working on a new payment formula for programs.
   As for local fund-raising, the presence of two stations ``makes
it very difficult to go out into the business community to attempt
to get underwriting,'' Johnson said.
   Corporation for Public Broadcasting figures show that viewer
donations to public TV stations nationwide grew from about $75
million in 1980 to more than $220 million in 1987, not counting
inflation.
   The number of subscribers grew from about 2.3 million to 4.5
million in the same period.
   Total public TV income grew from a little under $600 million in
1980 to over $1 billion in 1987, unadjusted for inflation.
</TEXT>
