<FIRST>r f AM-CasinoVote     11-05 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Casino Vote,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casino Debate Now Goes To Legislature After Clearing Referendum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GARY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casino gambling supporters, fresh from a
victory in a citywide referendum, plan to emphasize economic
development and local control when they ask a skeptical Gov. Evan
Bayh and the Indiana General Assembly to approve gambling
legislation.
   Voters in this economically depressed steel town endorsed casino
gambling by a 60 percent to 40 percent margin on Saturday, setting
the stage for a legislative battle in the 1990 General Assembly
over the proposal to allow casino-hotels to be built on the Lake
Michigan shore.
   ``An opportunity for jobs and economic revitalization _ that's
going to be the pitch,'' said Rep. Earline S. Rogers, a Democrat
from Gary. ``In the absence of the state coming up with a way to
solve our problems, we've come up with something ourselves.''
   Bayh said he believed the referendum result is important but not
compelling, given a voter turnout of just 32.3 percent.
   ``I'm opposed to casino gambling, but I'm willing to sit down
and look at all the arguments for and against, and I have yet to do
that,'' said Bayh. ``You never say never.''
   ``When you're in public office you have to hear people out and
see if they have a compelling argument that hasn't been
considered,'' the governor said.
   Mayor Thomas V. Barnes and other Gary casino advocates,
including representatives of the gambling industry, believe the
city could support five lakefront casino-hotels, which would
produce 25,000 casino-related jobs and an additional 10,000 jobs
for construction workers.
   Those figures, coupled with the support shown in the non-binding
referendum, make a strong case, casino advocates believe.
   The decline of the steel industry in the early '80s caused the
loss of thousands of jobs. Once the state's second-largest city,
Gary dropped to fourth as its population declined from 190,000 to
135,000.
   ``The more we tell our story, the more people look at the
numbers, the more inclined they are to look at the opportunity
favorably,'' said Robert Spolyar, a lobbyist for Resorts
International, a casino operator.
   Rogers said she also plans to appeal to the traditional Hoosier
belief in self-help and self-determination.
   ``This is a state that believes in local determination, that
believes in home rule, and we're going to make the legislators
prove that that's what they believe in,'' she said.
   But the casino advocates know the battle won't be easy. Like
Bayh, several legislative leaders say they're not convinced casino
gambling is best for Gary and for the state.
   Asked what she would say to the governor, who carried the
heavily Democratic Gary area by wide margins last year, Rogers
said, ``One word: Count. Count the supporters of this issue. Count
the jobs. Count the revenue.
   ``I'm certain wen he balances that with his personal
reservations, that will outweigh his personal beliefs,'' she said.
   Other legislators predicted the governor's position will
determine what the Legislature does.
   ``I don't think you're going to see a lot of people both in his
party and in the Republican Party feel there's any necessity to
send a bill down there that's going to be vetoed,'' said House
Republican Speaker Paul S. Mannweiler of Indianapolis. The house,
evenly divided between Republicans and Democrats, has a speaker
from each party.
   That decision could involve questions about the morality of
gambling more than arguments over jobs and local control, said
Mannweiler. Because of the morality issue, he argued, the casino
issue is different from past economic development appeals made by
legislators other parts of the state.
   ``Even though Gary says this is a local-option issue, that we
ought to help Gary help themselves, casino gambling is not somthing
I look very favorably on seeing in the state of Indiana anywhere,''
said Mannweiler.
   ``If we (in Indianapolis) would have asked for legalized
prostitution, I would certainly see why somebody someplace else in
the state would want to vote against it,'' he said.
   But other lawmakers contend Gary's problems are so urgent that
some people who would normally oppose casinos ``might be persuaded
to give it a try,'' said Senate Assistant Minority Leader Louis J.
Mahern, a Democrat from Indianapolis.
   ``I believe that anybody in the Legislature who rejects the idea
because of the moral issue of gambling almost has a burden on them
to come up with their solution to Gary's problems,'' said Mahern.
</TEXT>
