<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Housing     11-05 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Housing,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Group Forms Housing Finance Foundation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;L Convention, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The savings and loan industry's largest trade
group Sunday announced the formation of a foundation designed to
get thrift institutions more involved in housing loans to people of
modest means.
   The Housing Opportunities Foundation, established with $500,000
as an affiliate of the U.S. League of Savings Institutions, will
provide ``how-to'' information to savings institutions and track
trends and issues related to home ownership.
   But its main focus will be advising the 12 regional Federal Home
Loan Banks on how to administer a new affordable housing program
established by S&amp;L legislation enacted in August.
   The regional banks, created by Congress but owned by S&amp;Ls, are
required to provide $50 million a year from 1990 through 1993, $75
million in 1994 and $100 million a year thereafter.
   Robert B. O'Brien Jr., a New Jersey savings and loan executive
who will be chairman of the foundation, says he believes the money
should be used to provide discounted mortgages for people who would
not otherwise be able to own their homes.
   Next year, the $50 million subsidy should be able to provide a
discount on $2.5 billion worth of mortgages to 500,000 homebuyers,
he said.
</TEXT>
